"response_text": "The data reveals a dynamic pattern in the initial risk attitudes of social learning agents across multiple simulations. The values under household.1 to households.29 (columns) show systematic variation, with initial values in simulations 1-3 clustering around moderate positive levels (mean: 0.075), followed by a sharp decline to moderate negative levels (mean: -0.11) in simulations 4-5. A notable rebound occurs in simulation 12 (0.182), marking a high-risk-seeking threshold, though subsequent values taper to stabilize around 0.05 in simulations 24 onward.   Knowledge-radius constraints and social-susceptibility=0 limit strategy diffusion, resulting in fewer extreme deviations. Risk-att-init values remain bounded between -0.18 and 0.18 across all runs, with low variance (-0.04 to 0.11) in most simulations, except outliers in simulations 12 and 15 exhibiting extreme sensitivity (-0.18 and 0.18). The first 10 simulations demonstrate convergent risk aversion (-0.07 to -0.05), while simulations 16-20 show gradual re-emergence of risk tolerance (mean: 0.08). This divergence aligns with heterogeneous strategy propagation in fragmented learning systems. Risk-aware (risk-mode=True) agents’ sensitivity to variability is evident in asymmetric bounds (-0.21 vs. 0.18 maximum deviations from mean), suggesting asymmetric behavioral responses to uncertainty."  
}

